<section>

<h2>Overview: Inclusion in Sports</h2>
<div class="card">
Inclusive access to sports and recreation ensures that all children—regardless of ability, background, or identity—can participate meaningfully in physical activity.
It supports confidence, belonging, and social connection in schools while reducing barriers such as unequal participation opportunities, bullying, and exclusion during physical education.
</div>

<div class="card">
Key challenges include:
<ul>
<li>Unequal participation opportunities in school sports</li>
<li>Bullying or exclusion during physical activities</li>
<li>Accessibility barriers for students with different abilities</li>
<li>Lack of representation or cultural inclusion in activities</li>
</ul>
</div>

</section>

<section>

<h2>Historical Background</h2>

<div class="card">
Sports and school physical education have evolved alongside Canada’s growing cultural diversity.
Canada became officially multicultural in 1971, when the government introduced the <b>Multiculturalism Policy</b>, encouraging inclusion and equal opportunity for people from different cultural backgrounds.
</div>

<div class="card">
As Canada became one of the most multicultural countries in the world, schools increasingly reflected diverse cultures, languages, and identities.
School events such as Sports Day help build community connections and encourage students of all backgrounds to participate together.
</div>

